1 Published CMIP6Plus BC True published Differences with CMIP6-1-2: The dataset contains data until December 2022 based on GFED4s Global Fire Emissions. Furthermore CO2 has been added as separate species. This dataset has been developed for the testing phase of CMIP7. DRES-CMIP-BB4CMIP7-2-0 extends the data to 2023. Modellers are advised to use DRES-CMIP-BB4CMIP7-2-0. Tables for validation of the data of various species, geographical areas and sectors can be found on https://www.geo.vu.nl/~gwerf/GFED/GFED4/tables/ for the 1997 onwards period. DRES-CMIP-BB4CMIP7-1-0 Margreet.vanMarle@Deltares.nl, Guido.vanderWerf@wur.nl None emissions mon http://www.globalfiredata.org gn DRES CC BY 4.0 atmos 1.0 CMIP 175001-202212

604 Published CMIP6Plus ccl4 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 640 Published CMIP6Plus ccl4 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 676 Published CMIP6Plus cf4 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. CR-CMIP-0-3-0 zebedee.nicholls@climate-resource.com;malte.meinshausen@climate-resource.com None GHGConcentrations yr http://www.tbd.invalid gm CR CC BY 4.0 atmos 0.3.0 CMIP 0001-2022
721 Published CMIP6Plus cfc11 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 757 Published CMIP6Plus cfc113 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 838 Published CMIP6Plus cfc115 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 874 Published CMIP6Plus cfc11eq True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-0-3-0 zebedee.nicholls@climate-resource.com;malte.meinshausen@climate-resource.com None GHGConcentrations mon http://www.tbd.invalid gm CR CC BY 4.0 atmos 0.3.0 CMIP 000101-202212
919 Published CMIP6Plus cfc12 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 955 Published CMIP6Plus cfc12 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-0-3-0 zebedee.nicholls@climate-resource.com;malte.meinshausen@climate-resource.com None GHGConcentrations yr http://www.tbd.invalid gm CR CC BY 4.0 atmos 0.3.0 CMIP 0001-2022
1036 Published CMIP6Plus ch2cl2 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1072 Published CMIP6Plus ch3br True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-0-3-0 zebedee.nicholls@climate-resource.com;malte.meinshausen@climate-resource.com None GHGConcentrations mon http://www.tbd.invalid gm CR CC BY 4.0 atmos 0.3.0 CMIP 000101-202212
1134 Published CMIP6Plus ch3cl True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-0-3-0 zebedee.nicholls@climate-resource.com;malte.meinshausen@climate-resource.com None GHGConcentrations yr http://www.tbd.invalid gm CR CC BY 4.0 atmos 0.3.0 CMIP 0001-2022
1161 Published CMIP6Plus ch3cl True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1197 Published CMIP6Plus ch4 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-0-3-0 zebedee.nicholls@climate-resource.com;malte.meinshausen@climate-resource.com None GHGConcentrations mon http://www.tbd.invalid gr1z CR CC BY 4.0 atmos 0.3.0 CMIP 000101-202212
1242 Published CMIP6Plus chcl3 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1278 Published CMIP6Plus co2 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1313 Published CMIP6Plus datasource True published Differences with CMIP6-1-2: The dataset contains data until December 2022 based on GFED4s Global Fire Emissions. Modellers are advised to use DRES-CMIP-BB4CMIP7-2-0. Tables for validation of the data of various species, geographical areas and sectors can be found on https://www.geo.vu.nl/~gwerf/GFED/GFED4/tables/ for the 1997 onwards period. CR-CMIP-0-3-0 zebedee.nicholls@climate-resource.com;malte.meinshausen@climate-resource.com None GHGConcentrations mon http://www.tbd.invalid gm CR CC BY 4.0 atmos 0.3.0 CMIP 000101-202212
1340 Published CMIP6Plus halon1211 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1367 Published CMIP6Plus halon1211 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1403 Published CMIP6Plus halon1301 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1439 Published CMIP6Plus halon2402 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. 1448 Published CMIP6Plus halon2402 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1512 Published CMIP6Plus hcfc141b True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1593 Published CMIP6Plus hcfc22 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1629 Published CMIP6Plus hfc125 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1674 Published CMIP6Plus hfc134a True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1710 Published CMIP6Plus hfc134aeq True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1746 Published CMIP6Plus hfc134aeq True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1791 Published CMIP6Plus hfc143a True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1827 Published CMIP6Plus hfc152a True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1908 Published CMIP6Plus hfc23 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1944 Published CMIP6Plus hfc236fa True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 2025 Published CMIP6Plus hfc32 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 2061 Published CMIP6Plus hfc32 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 2097 Published CMIP6Plus hfc365mfc True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. 2106 Published CMIP6Plus hfc365mfc True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 2142 Published CMIP6Plus hfc4310mee True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 2184 Published CMIP6Plus n2o True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 2222 Published CMIP6Plus nf3 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 2258 Published CMIP6Plus pfc116 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 2278 Published CMIP6Plus pfc3110 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-0-3-0 zebedee.nicholls@climate-resource.com;malte.meinshausen@climate-resource.com None GHGConcentrations mon http://www.tbd.invalid gm CR CC BY 4.0 atmos 0.3.0 CMIP 000101-202212
2371 Published CMIP6Plus sf6 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). SOLARIS-HEPPA-CMIP-4-2 bernd@iaa.es None solar day http://solarisheppa.geomar.de/cmip7 gn SOLARIS-HEPPA CC BY 4.0 atmos 4.2 CMIP 18500101-20231231
2499 Retracted CMIP6Plus multiple False retracted v4.4 uses the final, absolute TSI scale (in consonance with NNL1) which should be used in CMIP7. Hence v4.3 is retracted. The change between v4.3 and v4.4 results in a 179 ppm increase of TSI and SSI compared to version 4.3. The preliminary TSI/SSI version in 4.3 had adapted the TSI scale from the CTIM instrument alone, the newer TSI scale is based on a TSIS-1 and CTIM composite (Coddington and Lean, 2024). This composite is also consistent with the TSI 'community consensus' composite (spot.colorado.edu/~koppg/TSI/TSI_Composite-SIST.txt). The original comment from the data provider is here. For further information, see SOLARIS-HEPPA release notes.
